 Cunegonde's Kidnapping tells in vivid detail the story of this hitherto unknown conflict. Drawing characters, scenes, and dialogue straight from a body of exceptional primary sources, it is the first microhistorical study of religious conflict and toleration in early modern Europe. In it, award-winning historian Benjamin J. Kaplan explores the dilemmas of interfaith marriage and the special character of religious life in a borderland, where religious dissenters enjoy unique freedoms. He also challenges assumptions about the impact of Enlightenment thought and suggests that, on a popular level, some parts of eighteenth-century Europe may not have witnessed a "rise of toleration."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Apr 2020) 0aInterfaith marriagezNetherlandszVaals (Gemeente)xHistoryy18th century. 0aKidnappingzNetherlandszVaals (Gemeente)xHistoryy18th century. 0aReformed ChurchxRelationsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300189971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300189971.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO